I’ve just updated Oli but I thought I’ll dump some info here so you are kept up to speed.

Staff with printing issues Oli now has the knowledge to resolve. It’s a simple fix, but one that I can’t do remotely easily so Oli has kindly agreed to do for me. Thanks again by the way! Essentially it is a group policy issue (group policy decides based on who you are/what device you’re using what you are allowed to have access to at Applefields etc) where it has not updated on some user profiles, this happens occasionally when group policy is updated as it’s not guaranteed to pull the new policies. To fix, you can restart x2 or Oli has a command he can run that will force it to update.

Scanning is also a relatively easy fix but myself and David are still working on it. The addresses PaperCut has pulled to use are your old email addresses. We just need to update all of the addresses to your Google Mail accounts so it scans to the correct emails. I’m waiting on David as we need to figure out where we put the new addresses to populate into PaperCut without removing the old ones from the original system as that could cause issues with Microsoft.

By all means give me a call when you’re back off your break Kirstie if you’d like me to run through things over the phone, sometimes easier to get the info across 😊

Sorry about the initial teething problems we’re having!

This email originated from outside of the organisation. Do not click links or open attachments unless you recognise the sender and know the content is safe.

Hello Vital

Lauren in the office contacted me on Friday to say she could no longer save to the shared admin drive, and Eleanor (SBM) has just emailed me to say she has the same problem this am.

I assume that it is because they had/have mapped drived to the old server which, since Friday (afternoon I think) has been made read-only. I've suggested logging off and logging back on to hopefully pick up the updated drive mappings and also sent a screenshot of browsing to \\server093 so that they could at least save anything that they had open to the new server share, but can I check that the drive mapping for the admin share has also had a policy update to force it to point to the new one.

Eleanor also raised a fairly important question - presumably this means that any work they did and saved to these shares last week is on the old server, not the new one? Is there anything you can do to copy those changes across, or do they need to try to do it manually? I don't want people to lose a week's work! It has caused quite a lot of confusion, and I don't want them to lose confidence in the new network at the outset...

One further question - any progress with getting the print release working via server 093 or do I need to get the school to contact the MFD providers? I installed direct print Qs on server093 for lots of people (and sent an all.staff email showing how they could do this) to enable them to have a workaround in the short term, but they REALLY miss the security and cost-savings of the print release system!

I'm not due back in LDs until Thursday, but if you particularly need me to go in to investigate/implement anything I could possibly squeeze a trip in somehow.

Thanks
Kat

the LMS project (SSO), please just find the information below regarding
configuring SSO for when the time is suitable. * SAML 2.0 protocol (intro
article<
https://www.docebo.com/knowledge-base/introduction-to-docebo-for-saml/

From: Konica Minolta Business Solutions UK <marcoms@konicaminolta.co.uk>

To: J Meehan <j.meehan@huntington-ed.org.uk>
Subject: Paper Cut Vulnerability Update: Active Exploitation

On 6th April we notified you of a critical issue in PaperCut MF & PaperCut NG.
Dear PaperCut User,

On 6th April we notified you of a critical issue in PaperCut MF & PaperCut NG. At the time there was no evidence of activate exploitation. Unfortunately, Konica Minolta has now become aware of multiple instances of this vulnerability being actively exploited.

We are therefore advising all customers that it’s imperative that any installation of PaperCut that’s still effected by this issue be upgraded to a patched version as soon as possible. The email of April 6th contained instructions on the quickest path to upgrade your specific PaperCut installation. Additional information is available here<http://link.konicaminolta.co.uk/Njk3LUdCVi03NTAAAAGLPibvbEDgo9i7nDfid-Rd64Rge9I9hVeODaPgTvsMyh3vwt_U8EhCJUdz3knBxofoIfGdMYg=>.

Its important that all customers assess their own appetite to risk when deciding whether to continue operating vulnerable systems. However, we do strongly advise against any customer continuing to operate a vulnerable PaperCut system that’s accessible to untrusted users (e.g. by being accessible via the internet).

If you believe your unpatched PaperCut system may have been compromised via this vulnerability, please quarantine the PaperCut server(s) immediately and contact our Hotline Team.

If you would like further information, please contact our Hotline Team (on 01268822707 & select Option 4).

Best Regards
Your Konica Minolta Support Team.

*Please Note: these issues do not affect PaperCut Hive, PaperCut Pocket, Print Deploy, Mobility Print, PaperCut Views, or PaperCut client software.

The Schools Gigabit Broadband Programme is a Department for Education (DfE) scheme to provide faster broadband for schools.  We think your school may be eligible and we don’t want you to lose the opportunity to be included.   

Your local authority may have posted information about this programme on your school’s bulletin to prepare you for my call.
   
I have attached the following documents for your information, which outline the programme:   
  

  *   PowerPoint slide deck, which introduces the programme,   
  *   A data checklist for completion and return by email.


Alternatively, if you prefer to provide this information via a call, please advise of dates and times you are free, a contact number for the call and I will send you an invite.

The data you need to complete the checklist may be found in your broadband contract or bill.  It may be that you need to liaise with your IT department/person or internet provider.

If you require further information but don’t have time for a telephone call, the link below will take you to the government press release about the programme.
Thousands of rural primary schools to get huge broadband upgrade - GOV.UK (www.gov.uk)<https://www.gov.uk/government/news/thousands-of-rural-primary-schools-to-get-huge-broadband-upgrade>

To: J Meehan <j.meehan@huntington-ed.org.uk>
Cc: James Clarke <helpdesk@academia.co.uk>
Subject: P27 PCs Managed Service

Hi Jonathan

Our numbers for A Level Music Tech have been steadily increasing (brilliant!) but we've recruited 16 for Sept 23 - this is likely to be 17 now that an external student wants to switch from Music to Music Tech, with Music now not running in 23.

Great stuff for MT but our teaching space in P27/the studio only has 12 PCs in it - 11 student and 1 teacher. Although regular Music classroom P23 has 20 student PCs, timetabling always has MT on against GCSE or KS3 Music which means that P23 is just about always needed by other classes. The solution would be squeezing more PCs into P27 - we think 5 machines would cover us.

James came up to scope the space yesterday and we checked network ports and power points - both of which we seem to have plenty spare. James couldn't see a problem on those fronts. Space is the main issue so we are trailing some mini musical keyboards that are only as wide as a PC monitor screen (the existing keyboards are twice as wide and cause the space issue). Furnishing all PCs with these would allow us to squeeze in the 5 extra machines - we already have plenty of stools in there and luckily no legs on the desks to restrict seating.

James mentioned us possibly being able to get these extra PCs through the managed service, meaning no cost to the Music dept. We'd obviously cover the costs of music keyboards/audio interfaces/extra software licenses. The biggest need for this is the huge class of 17 we'll have in Y12 from September - we wouldn't be able to teach them in the existing space and don't have an alternative room - it'd be a mess for them. In a perfect world, we'd be able to have 2 groups of 8 but school can't afford that. Recruitment for MT does get stronger each year and the 2 GCSE groups of 2022-24 and secured 2 GCSE groups of 2023-25 will likely result in similar numbers for future MT cohorts. The extra PCs would not be left dormant after 2024. KS4 and 5 students often use P27 in study periods/P6 etc for coursework so the extra machines would help with that also.

Looking into future recruitment, we'll have to ensure a maximum number for the MT course as there is no more room for expansion - we'd have to cap it at 16 in future if we have these extra machines.

How does all of this sound?

Thanks
Ian

Dear Sir / Madam,

The Department for Education (DfE) is conducting an important study, called
the *Technology in Schools Survey* (TiSS). The research aims to understand
the state of technology within the school sector, including its quality and
availability and how it supports teaching and learning, school management
and administration.

This survey is also going out to leaders and teachers but the DfE is
particularly interested in gathering the views of IT leads like yourself.
The findings will help DfE to better support school staff in maximising the
benefits of using technology in educational settings. This could be through
reducing workload, improving access for pupils or something else.

https://www.iffresearch.com/TiSS

   - This is a short online survey that *takes 15-20 minutes to complete*
   - Any information provided will be kept confidential and anonymous
   - We would kindly ask you to *complete it as soon as possible*

Hi Jonathan

Our numbers for A Level Music Tech have been steadily increasing (brilliant!) but we've recruited 16 for Sept 23 - this is likely to be 17 now that an external student wants to switch from Music to Music Tech, with Music now not running in 23.

Great stuff for MT but our teaching space in P27/the studio only has 12 PCs in it - 11 student and 1 teacher. Although regular Music classroom P23 has 20 student PCs, timetabling always has MT on against GCSE or KS3 Music which means that P23 is just about always needed by other classes. The solution would be squeezing more PCs into P27 - we think 5 machines would cover us.

James came up to scope the space yesterday and we checked network ports and power points - both of which we seem to have plenty spare. James couldn't see a problem on those fronts. Space is the main issue so we are trailing some mini musical keyboards that are only as wide as a PC monitor screen (the existing keyboards are twice as wide and cause the space issue). Furnishing all PCs with these would allow us to squeeze in the 5 extra machines - we already have plenty of stools in there and luckily no legs on the desks to restrict seating.

James mentioned us possibly being able to get these extra PCs through the managed service, meaning no cost to the Music dept. We'd obviously cover the costs of music keyboards/audio interfaces/extra software licenses. The biggest need for this is the huge class of 17 we'll have in Y12 from September - we wouldn't be able to teach them in the existing space and don't have an alternative room - it'd be a mess for them. In a perfect world, we'd be able to have 2 groups of 8 but school can't afford that. Recruitment for MT does get stronger each year and the 2 GCSE groups of 2022-24 and secured 2 GCSE groups of 2023-25 will likely result in similar numbers for future MT cohorts. The extra PCs would not be left dormant after 2024. KS4 and 5 students often use P27 in study periods/P6 etc for coursework so the extra machines would help with that also.

Looking into future recruitment, we'll have to ensure a maximum number for the MT course as there is no more room for expansion - we'd have to cap it at 16 in future if we have these extra machines.

How does all of this sound?

Thanks
Ian


Subject Leader for Music Technology

Dear Colleagues,

The professional and resilient way in which staff and students right
across the trust have responded to the IT difficulties we are experiencing
has been inspiring and I thank you for your patience as we have negotiated
this difficult situation.

I would also like to recognise the team of staff and technicians at Vital
that have worked significantly longer hours to get us to this point.

As we start to reinstate and make available the Windows network there are
some required security improvements that have been implemented as part of
the rebuild.

One of the changes required will have an impact on staff logins and network
access, so in preparation for this rollout please read through the attached
two documents.  If you already have MFA set up then this shouldn't change

[required] Title: Police Cyber Alarm set up - email 1
Description:
Hi,

As discussed today, I need to set up Police Cyber Alarm for our 3 schools,
and having spoken to someone in the NYCC IT team today, they advised
speaking to you as it's tied in with server support.

I've been sent an access code for each of the 3 schools (see email below
for one of these) and now need to do the next stage of the installation.
The email below and attached doc directs me to the members area of the
Cyber Alarm site, and there's then a form to fill in.  One of the
questions on the form is about where our Cyber Alarm data collector will be
installed, so I need to ask your advice about that - NYCC said it's often
done by having a virtual server on the school server.  There's also
guidance on the attached about the spec needed for the virtual collector.

I've got the external facing IP addresses that are asked for on the form
from NYCC.

I know a lot of you are away at the moment but I'd appreciate speaking to
someone next week to try to get this sorted - I will be on email next week
or you can call me on 07922 039150 - please leave a message if I'm not
around and I'll ring you back.

I'll forward the emails for the other two schools shortly.

Many thanks,
Carrie
